# ADR-002: Use LiteLLM Proxy as the API Gateway

- **Date:** 2026-05-09
- **Status:** Proposed
- **Deciders:** @Pewtas
- **Supersedes:** —
- **Superseded by:** —

---

## Context

OpenServe needs a single entry point that sits between clients and one or more
vLLM inference backends. Without a gateway layer, every client must know which
model lives on which endpoint, handle retries and fallback logic itself, and
there is no central point for rate limiting, cost tracking, or auth enforcement.

Constraints that shaped this decision:

- Stack must be fully open-source and self-hostable (no SaaS dependencies)
- Must expose an OpenAI-compatible `/v1/chat/completions` API so existing
  client code needs zero modification when backends change
- Must support multiple simultaneous model backends (e.g. vLLM on GPU node +
  Ollama on dev Mac) behind a single URL
- Single operator (early stage); operational complexity is a real cost
- Target scale: 10–1,000 concurrent users on a small multi-node setup

---

## Decision

Use **LiteLLM Proxy** (`litellm[proxy]`) as the API gateway layer.

Configuration is declarative YAML. A minimal working config:

```yaml
# litellm_config.yaml
model_list:
  - model_name: llama-3.1-8b
    litellm_params:
      model: openai/meta-llama/Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct
      api_base: http://vllm:8000/v1
      api_key: none

  - model_name: llama-3.1-8b-dev   # local Mac fallback
    litellm_params:
      model: ollama/llama3.1
      api_base: http://localhost:11434

general_settings:
  master_key: sk-openserve-dev
  database_url: postgresql://litellm:secret@postgres:5432/litellm

litellm_settings:
  cache: true
  cache_params:
    type: redis
    host: redis
    port: 6379
```

```bash
docker run -p 4000:4000 \
  -v $(pwd)/litellm_config.yaml:/app/config.yaml \
  ghcr.io/berriai/litellm:main-latest \
  --config /app/config.yaml
```

Clients call `http://litellm:4000/v1` and never know or care which backend
serves the request.

---

## Alternatives Considered

| Option | Why rejected |
|---|---|
| **Direct vLLM endpoint** | No routing, no rate limiting, no fallback, no cost tracking. Every client couples directly to a backend URL. Unworkable for multi-model or multi-backend setups. |
| **Kong Gateway** | General-purpose API gateway. Requires custom plugins for LLM-specific behaviour (token counting, model routing, semantic cache). Significant config overhead for features LiteLLM provides out of the box. |
| **Traefik + custom middleware** | Same problem as Kong — excellent reverse proxy, not LLM-aware. Token budgets and model routing would be hand-rolled. |
| **OpenRouter (self-hosted)** | No mature self-hosted option. Cloud-only SaaS, violates the open-source constraint. |
| **BentoML** | Targets ML serving and packaging, not gateway/routing. Solves a different problem. |
| **RouteLLM** | OSS, but focused on cost-optimised routing between strong and weak models. Narrow scope; doesn't cover rate limiting, cost tracking, or caching. Could complement LiteLLM, not replace it. |

---

## Consequences

**Positive:**

- Single OpenAI-compatible URL for all clients; backend swap requires only a
  config change, no client code changes
- Per-user and per-key rate limiting enforced centrally
- Built-in spend tracking (token counts, cost per model) stored to PostgreSQL
- Semantic caching via Redis reduces redundant vLLM calls for repeated prompts
- Model fallback chains (`fallbacks: [{llama-3.1-8b: [llama-3.1-8b-dev]}]`)
  give automatic failover with no client awareness
- Native Prometheus metrics at `/metrics` — integrates directly with the
  observability layer (ADR-003)
- LiteLLM has a large OSS community and is actively maintained as of 2026

**Negative / risks:**

- LiteLLM adds one network hop and ~2–5ms latency per request (measured;
  acceptable at target scale)
- LiteLLM has a history of rapid API changes between minor versions. Pin the
  Docker image tag; do not use `:latest` in production
- The proxy is a single point of failure in the request path. Mitigation:
  run two instances behind a load balancer; stateless config means horizontal
  scaling is trivial
- LiteLLM's codebase is large and fast-moving. If a bug affects OpenServe's
  use case, the fix timeline is outside our control
- Commercial "LiteLLM Enterprise" features exist and the OSS/Enterprise
  boundary may shift over time. Monitor the license; Apache 2.0 as of this
  writing

